o Tha Star.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 23.\u2014Only In ex\nceptional cases do either dividends\nor earnings play their normal part\nIn Influencing prices in the present\nmarket.\nTaking the matter of dividends first,\nthe main reason for this unusual sit\nuation is, of course, the tax on un\ndistributed profits. In the old days,\nwhen the directors declared an extra\ndividend it was taken as an expres\nsion of confidence in the business\nfuture. The interpretation was that\nthe, outlook for that particular cor\nporation, as well as for the industry\nrepresented, was t(rlght enough to\nJustify the show of generosity. Some\ntimes, as happened in 1929 and early\n1930, extras were declared for the\ndirect purpose of Inspiring faith on\nthe part of the shareholders.\nThe assumption now Is that larger\npayments at the year end are simply\na means of avoiding the tax. It is\nregarded not as an expression of\nsound business Judgment, but as a\nconcession to the law, and so does\nnot become a bull point on the stock\nconcerned.\nTry Interim Plan.\nThis flood of extra dividends will\nabate after the turn of the year.\nDistributions to stockholders will then\nmake an unfavorable showing, com\npared with those now being made.\nSome corporations, and the number\nis increasing, are adopting the British\nplan of interim dividends, with a final\ndeclaration in the last quarter of the\nyear. The idea is to wait until a full\nyear\u2019s profits can be estimated before\ndeciding how much can be paid out\nto shareholders on an annual basis.\nAlthough it breaks into the regu\nlarity of investment income for hold\ners of equities, there is a good deal\nto be said in favor of this plan. On\nthe other hand, it eliminates the divi\ndend rate as a factor in the stock\nmarket, or to a great extent at least.\nThe earnings situation is a little\ndifferent in the case of industrial\ncompanies from that in rails or utili\nties. Industrials report only quar\nterly at the best, and sometimes only\nannually, so that the reports coming\nto hand at present, as a rule, cover\nperiods when operations were being\nconducted at a profit.\nIn view of what has happened to\nbusiness since the late summer and\nearly fall, no such good results can\nbe expected in quarterly statements\nyet to come. Nor is the outlook for\nthe new year so bright, for business\nrevival will be slow in getting under\nway, and meanwhile the tax burden\nwill not grow any lighter.\nThe market, therefore, is trying to\nstrike a balance between the highly\nfavorable results of the first three\nquarters and the anticipated adversi\nties of the last quarter of 1937 and\nthe early month of 1938. It makes\nreliance on the earnings yardstick\nas a test of stock prices misleading.\n(Copyright. 11X17. by the North American\nNewspaper Alliance. Inc.)\nDIVIDENDS ANNOUNCED\nNEW YORK. Dec. 23.\u2014Dividends de\nclarwi (prepared by the Standard Statis\ntICS LO.\nExtra.\nPe- Stock of Pay.\n_ Rate Hod. record, able\nPreferred Accident Ins 20c 12-24 1-lb\nSteel Co of Canada $2 1-7 2-1\n.Special.\nConsol Car Heating. $2 _ 12-20 12-\u201c>4\nSpringfield Fire A\nMarine Ins 25e ._ 12-22 1-3\nInitial.\nCampbell As fine *>-04 12-27\nCarpenter L E 6%c Q 12-28 l\"-30\nReed Drug 35c 12-23 12-28\nStock.\nNewmont Mining* 11-30 12-15\n4\nAccumulated.\nRegal Shoe 7*1 pf 45.25 12-10 12-21\nTex Hyro-Kl *3.50 pf 26c 12-23 12-27\nRegular.\nAsso Rl Est 0*7 pf *.'1 8 12-24 12-28\nBasic Ind bearer 13.138c 12-31\nBrew. C. Co Ltd *1 M 1-20 1-25\nCarreras adr f A 0 r. 74.4c 12-H 12-28\n-i00- B 8.5c 12-8 12-28\nClinton Tr NY 75c Q 12-28 1-3\nColumbia Mills *1 12-23 12-\"4\nc\u00b0os Cigar 7% pf *1.75 Q 2-15 3-1\nDo. 6%fr pf *1.021 s Q 1-15 2-1\nFiremen's Ins Wash 60c 12-24 1-3\nGraytel Pay Station 25c Q 12-30 1-15\nHecker Prod vtc 15c Q 1-10 2-1\nKellogg Swbd A Sup 15c 1-11 1-31\nr 1,0 r>''_cv.,Bf *1 25 Q 1-11 1-31\nLawyers Tr N Y 35c 12-24 1-3\nMaryland Tr Balt 40c S 12-24 12-28\nNew E Pow (C, pf *1.50 q 12-23 1-3\nSupervised Shrs 12c 12-31 1