Including 100 direct: fat\nlambs opening moderately active, fully\nSteady asking hither: good to choice of\nferings. K.60-8 76. early bulk at outside:\nbest held above 9.no. indications about\nsteady on sheen, feeding lambs scarce.\nODD-LOT DEALINGS.\nBy the Associated Press\nThe Securities commission reported to\nday Ihese transection* by customers with\nodd-lot dealer* or special tat* on the Mew\nYork Slock thwhange for December 22:\n8.111 purchase* involving 215,270 shares:\n6.409 sale* involvma 164.002 share*.\n\nMETAL MARKET.\nNEW YORK. Dee. 23 OP* \u2014Cooper,\nsteady; electrolytic, spot and future.\n10.12V4-11.00; export 10.05-10.10. Tin.\nsteady: spot and future. 42.25. Lead,\nsteady: New York, spot 4.75-80: East St.\nLouis. 4.60. Zinc, steady: East St. Louis,\nspot and future. 5.00. Antimony, nominal.\nIron, aluminum, quicksilver, platinum and\nwolframite unchanged.\nNEW YORK SUGAR.\nNEW YORK. Dec. 23 UP).\u2014Sugar fu\ntures were steady on trade covering which\nabsorbed scattered. liquidation and hedge\nselling.\nJanuary No.' 3 sold at 2.28 and March\nat 2.29. or net unohanted. March Ho. 4\nsold at 1.17%. or 1 point net higher.\nMONTREAL SILVER\nMONTREAL. Dec. 23 OP*.\u2014Silver tu\n40.60.\nNears Year-Around Status.\nApple Gains Favor in\nU. S. Wine Output.\nBy J. G. DONLEY.\nSptelal Dispatch to Tht Star.\nNEW YORK. Dec 23\u2014Because\nmeat*, particularly beef, are a little\nless expensive than they were some\nweeks ago, a great many families feel\ning the strain of filling Christmas\nstockings will give turkey the go-by,\ncome Saturday. But the food folks tell\nus that the turkey Is getting to be a\nyear-around bird.\nEven so. the turkey crop, on a per\ncapita basis, has not yet succeeded\nin getting back to the proportions of\nthe gay 80s. In 1890 growers raised\none turkey for every five persons.\nThen came the \"blackhead disease,\u201d\nboll-weevil of the turkey flocks, and\nturkeys became a luxury only to be\nencompassed by holiday purses.\nBut with commercial hatching of\nturkey poults not \"chicks'\u2019 and\nwith the old dread disease under con\ntrol, we got up to a per capita ratio\nof one turkey to every six citizens\nlast year, the largest crop since the\n90s. In Spam, incidentally, the\nChristmas turkey is served with a kick.\nShortly before the slaughter the birds\nare forcibly fed wine The turkeys\nmay go momentarily \"loco,\u201d but they\nare said to be more palatable.\nApple nine in Favor.\nHere in America, where wine is\ngrowing steadily in consumption,\nthanks largely to the \u201cnational marker'\nideas and promotions of Pacific Coast\nvintners, the superabundant apple is\nat last contributing its bit to the flow\nof higher-bracket beverages. Out in\nOregon approximately 250,000 gallons\nof apple wine will be produced this\nyear, with initial distribution limited\nto the coastal area but with national\ndistribution envisioned for the future\nApple wine is light golden color and\nhas what it takes.\nSpeaking of meat for Christmas, on\nthe basis of a small roast costing less\nthan a well-fed turkey, some one\nrecently has figured out that auto\nmobiles are cheaper than meat, on a\nper pound basis. A ton-and-a-half\nautomobile sells for $900, or an av\nerage of 30 cents per pound. Ford\ntakes a decrepit car and under tons\nof pressure turns it into a capsule\nto feed the steel furnaces.\nWe haven't got capsule foods yet\nand the food scientists say that we\nnever will have them in the popularly\nconceived form of a few vest-pocket\ntablets to carry us through the day.\nThe reason is that, compressed and\ncondensed to its utmost, the makings\nof a real sustaining meal would still\nbe a sizable cube.\nBut we do have numbers of food\nproducts which economize on pack\naging space\u2014such as powdered and\ncondensed milk, condensed and des\nicated soups, dried fruits and vege\ntables. etc. One of the latest con\ncentrated food products is clam broth\nin the form of small, dry wafters\nthe size of a penny, so efficiently con\ncentrated that one wafer will, in due\ntime, turn a bowl of piping-hot water\ninto steaming broth.\nSweet Potatoes Dehydrated.\nAnd we are dehydrating sweet po\ntatoes, including the skins, to grind\nthe resulting meal into flour. Ac\ncording to the Northwestern Miller,\nthe originator explains that the sweet\npotato flour contains no gluten; that\ncookies and baking powder biscuits\nhave been made successfully from\nit, but that some blending with wheat\nflour will be necessary for raised\nbreads and cakes. In England they\nare preserving white, or Irish, po\ntatoes by completely drying and pow\ndering them after they have been\npeeled and steam-oooked.\nThe notable news on wheat flour\nconsumption is that the trend has\napparently turned upward, on a per\ncapita basis, in this country, after\ndeclining steadily for 30 years\u2014from\n230 pounds in 1902 to 150 pounds\nin 1934, a decline of 30 per cent.\nThe Millers' National Federation re\nports 1935-6 flour consumption of 152\npounds, while the 1936-7 crop year\nraised the ante to 153 pounds. Credit\ngoes to co-operative promotional ef\nforts through the Wheat Flour In\nstitute.\nOne food product which no longer\nneeds promotional efforts is the\nubiquitous \u201chot dog.\u201d It is nearly\na century since the first wiener camel\nover from Vienna to grace our break\nfast tables. Now its cousin has be\ncome \"big business\u201d\u2014375,0C0 stands\nsold over 1.000,000,000 last year, and\nanother 500,000,000 were bought for\nhome serving.\n(Copyrtsht. 1937.)\nU. S. TREASURY NOTES.\nYORK. Dec. 23 (A4.\u2014 Prices euoted\nin dollars and thirty-seconds.\nApprox.\nPet. Month. Year. Bid. Asked, yield.\n244 Feb.. 1938 _100.8\n3. Mar.. 1938 101.9 101.11\n2\u20194 June. 1938 _ 101.20 101.22\n2V4 Sept., 1938 _101.29 101.31\n1V\u00ab Dec.. 1938 _101.3 101.5 .07\n1'4 Mar., 1939 _101.12 101.14 .32\n2<4 June. 1939 _ 102.12 102.14 .46\n144 Sept.. 1939 _101.12 101.14 .33\n1% Dec.. 1939 _101.12 101.14 .64\n144 Mar., 1940 _ 101.26 101.27 .78\n1# June. 1940 _101.18 101.20 .83\n1% Dee.. 1940 101.17 101.19 .95\n1M. Mar.. 1941_101.10 101.12 1.08\n144 June. 1941_100225 100.27 1.1.3\n144 Dee., 1941_ 100.8 100.8 1.18\n144 Mar., 1942 _101.18 101.20 1.35\n2 Sept.. 1942 _ 102.27 102.29 1.35\n144 Dec.. 1942 _101.15 101.17 1.44\n\nBangor A Aroostook Railroad\nCommon share earnings. 11 months\nended Nowembaa SO. were gS JO,\nagainst S2.7T\nStructural Steel\nBusiness Climbs\nDuring November\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 23\u2014 New busi\nness booked during November by the\nstructural steel fabricating industry\nwas the largest since last July, the\nAmerican Institute of Steel Construc\ntion reported today.\nBoth bookings and shipments, how\never, were slightly below the average\nfor the year. Bookings were 58.4 per\ncent of normal (the yearly average\n1928-31 inclusive), and shipments 55\nper cent of normal as against a\nmonthly average of 59 per cent and 60\nper cent, respectively, for the year.\nBookings for November were 136.542\ntons and for the 11-month period.\n1,517,923 tons, compared with 1936\nfigures of 121,607 and 1,442,474 tons\nrespectively. November shipments\ntotaled 128,556 tons, compared with\n134,115 last year, while shipments for\nthe first 11 months stood at 1,543.959\ntons against 1,426,430 in the 1936\nperiod.\nCONSOLIDATED CIGAR\nRESUMES DIVIDEND\nBs ihe Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 23.\u2014Consolidated\nCigar Corp. today declared a dividend\nof 75 cents a share on the common\nstock, payable January 14, 1938, to\nholders of record January 5. Previous\ndividend was declared April 1, 1932,\nin the same amount.\nSHORT-TERM SECURITIES.\nReported by Chss. D. Barney Co.)\nAmer Tel A Tel 54s 1943. 1124\nAuburn Auto Co 44s 1939 194 35\nBaldwin Loco Works 6s 1940 103\nCall! Peeking Corp ,5s 1940. 104 1044\n\u00a3f\u2122 Ohio 5s 19.18 lol4 1 o 1 4\nChese A Ohio Rwy 6s 1939 1054 106\nrd\u2018*\u00b0 d \u00ae;ec Ilium 4s 1939. 1034 1064\nQ*n Public Serv 5 Is 1939. 954 974\nGrand Rap At Ind 44s 1941. 106\nHouston 011 54s 1940 99 ino\nInter Merc Marine 6s 1941 51 564\nInter Tel A Tel 44s 1939 89 894\nL\u00bb\u00ab>eae Gas Light 5s 1939 91 914\nItehigh Valley Coal 6s 1938 694\nLehigh Val Ter Ry 5s 1941 87\nl8>ng Island Gen 4s 1938 190 30\nLouis ft Nash R R 4s 1940 1043, 105\nMichlgan cent R R 4s 1940. 4 j !\"s.\nMidland RR of N J 5s 1940 17 34\nA.Nor RR 44s 1939 764\n\u00a3*v.StL \u00ab4 notes 1938 86 894\nNew York Dock 5s 1938 44 4 474\nNew York Tel Co 44s 1939 100*5 1074\nPac RR of Missouri 4s 1938 81 87\nPennsylvania Co 34s 1941 1034 104 4\nPenn-Dixie Cement 6s 1941. 88 4 884\nPenn. R R Co 4's 1943 1094 1094\nPhila_Balt A Wash 4s 1943 1094 1104\nRio Grande West 4s 1939 36 884\nTerm RR As St L 44s 1939 1 084\nVanadium Coro 5s 1941 83 84\nVertlentes Sugar Co 7s 1943 9 4 11\nWabash Rwy Co 5s 1939 70 70 r,\nWarner Bros 6s 1939 74 4 75 4\nWestern NI Y Pa 4s 1943. 1074 1084\nWestern Union Tel 5s 1938 99s. 1004\nMoney for CoastractioB Loans\nand\nLoans on Existing Properties\n5%\nnt*r died or non onlt\nGEORGE I. BORGER\n643 Indiana Are. N.W.\nNat\u2019l 0350\nFABRICATORSLACK\nSTOCKS OF METAL\nMust Enter Market Soon for\nat Least Enough to\nBalance Outgo.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, Dec. 23.\u2014Metal stocks\nof fabricators have been drawn down\nthis fall to an extent which will re\nquire their entering the market soon\nfor at least enough tonnage to balance\noutgoing shipments, according to a\nsurvey of the metal fabricating indus\ntry just completed by the Standard\nStatistics Co.\nReflecting the sharp contraction in\nactivity In the automobile and con\nstruction industries, operations of\nmetal fabricators have been at pro\ngressively declining rates over the past\nfew months. No monthly statistics on\nthe output of the copper and brass\nmills and the wire and cable plants\nare published, but the reduced rate of\nfabricating activity is reflected in the\nsharp contraction in sales of copper\nand of high-grade zinc by the pro\nducers of those metals.\nCopper Deliveries Drop.\nDeliveries of copper by producers to\ndomestic fabricators in November had\ndropped to only 33,900 tons, which\ncompared with 66,300 tons in Septem\nber and an average of about 80,000\ntons through the spring months. De\nliveries of high-grade zinc (a large\nproportion of which is used in the\nbrass plants) amounted to 13,597 tons\nin November, against 16,800 tons in\nSeptember and 30,880 tons in May.\nThe decline in output of the mills,\nhowever, has not been so sharp as\nthe cut in their purchases of raw ma\nterials. It is estimated that products\nshipped out by the fabricators during\nNovember contained from 45,000 to\n50,000 tons of copper. In other words,\nfabricators drew on inventories and\nmetal in process to the extent of 10,\n000 to 15.000 tons during the month.\nMinimum Near Absolute.\nBecause the working stocks of raw\nmaterial required to turn out 50,000\ntons of finished products monthly are\nonly about half as great as the work\ning stocks required to turn out 100,000\ntons monthly, fabricators have been\nable to fill orders without substantial\nnew purchases for three months. Nev\nertheless there are indications that\nworking stocks are being cut to an\nirreducible minimum in some plants\nand that fabricators will be forced\nearly in 1938 to buy at least enough\nmetal to cover current requirements.\nThus, as against only 21,035 tons\nof copper bought in the entire month\nof November, fabricators ordered 14,\n491 Sons in the first 14 days of De\ncember. Most of the metal was speci\nfied for December or January deliv\nery, indicating that the buyers needed\nmetal for current orders. Metal prices\nhave fallen sharply to current levels\nof 10.25 cents for copper, against a\npeak of 17 cents for the year, and 5\ncents for zinc, against a peak of 7.5\ncents for the year. The larger copper\nproducers are maintaining a price of\n11 cents a pound for copper, however,\nand the leading fabricators are basing\ntheir prices on this quotation.\nREAL ESTATE LOANS\nmm RESIDENCE and\nSMALL BUSINESS\n%J /If PROPERTIES\nFRED T. NESBIT\n010 VERMONT AVE DISTRICT 939?\nTEN YEARS AT *\\l\nOn City Central\nBneinees Property\nWe invite applications for\nnew construction or refinancing\nWell Located\nWASHINGTON REAL ESTATE\n[Shannon a luchS)\nMortgage Loan Co treason Sent*\nMASSACHUSETTS MUTUAL\nLIFE INSURANCE CO.\n1505 H St. N.W. Natl. 2345\nFirst Mortgage Loans\nDistrict of Columbia, Nearby Maryland and Virginiu\nHomes Business\nApartments J Properties\nTerms from 3 to 15 years\nAlso\nMonthly Payment Loans\nRandall ZX. Hagner Company\nINCORPORATED\nMORTOAOI LOAN CORMAPOIIDtRT\n1321 Connecticut Ave. N.W. Telephone DEcatur 3600\nJ\u2014-\u2022\nPATTERN FOR\ndriving\nA life that is patterned on sensible spending and steady\nsaving has every chance of being a happy one.\nSavings can pave the way to business opportunities,\n1 tome ownership, marriage, education, travel, old-age secur\nity\u2014in fact to nearly all the worth-while things in life.\nHere at this bank we welcome new savers, young and\nold. The sooner you start your account, the sooner you\nwill start collecting the dividends life pays to those who\nplan, and save, ahead.\nMcLachlen Banking Corporation\nSince 1891\nTENTH AND G STREETS. N. W.\nS. W. Branch, 12th and Maryland Ave. S.W.\nMember Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation\n_\u00a3-\u2014-\u00a3","height":"31316","width":"22388"}}
